When a small group of living creatures (a small stock) are separated from the main stock from which they originate (for example, if they move across a mountain range or river, or if they move to a new island so that they cannot easily get back), they often end up in a different environment than the one they were in.
This new environment has other resources and other competitors, so to be a strong competitor, the new population needs other features or adaptations than they had previously needed.
Indigenous population has not changed at all, they still need the same adaptations as before.
Over time, when the new population begins to adapt to its new environment, they begin to look smaller and smaller as the second population.
Eventually, after thousands or even millions of years, the two populations will look so different that they cannot be called the same species.
We call this process specialization, which simply means the formation of new species. Specialization is an inevitable consequence and a very important part of evolution.
